docs.abstract: Two new United States attorneys start work on Friday in New York, with big cases looming in such areas as terrorism, political corruption and civil rights.
docs.snippet: Two new United States attorneys start work on Friday in New York, with big cases looming in such areas as terrorism, political corruption and civil rights.
docs.lead_paragraph: The two interim United States attorneys who will assume office in New York City on Friday will inherit major cases and pending decisions that seem likely to define the focus of their work over the next few years and could begin to shape their legacies.

headline.main: Newly Appointed U.S. Prosecutors Inherit Major Cases
headline.print_headline: Major Cases Await Interim U.S. Attorneys Taking Over in New York

byline.original: By Benjamin Weiser and Alan Feuer

docs.abstract: The “black-ish” spinoff is still finding its identity a few weeks into its first season. But it has the potential to do with college comedy what its parent did with 21st-century race.
docs.snippet: The “black-ish” spinoff is still finding its identity a few weeks into its first season. But it has the potential to do with college comedy what its parent did with 21st-century race.
docs.lead_paragraph: The challenge of going off to college is leaving the nest without coming unmoored. This is also the challenge of spinning off a college sitcom.

docs.abstract: With crime at lows not seen in decades, but drug addiction and untreated mental illness still persistent problems, some say it may be time to rethink the size of forces.
docs.snippet: With crime at lows not seen in decades, but drug addiction and untreated mental illness still persistent problems, some say it may be time to rethink the size of forces.
docs.lead_paragraph: With the close of the year, the tally was in: Crime was down in the 30 largest cities in the United States, and even a worrisome uptick in urban murders had subsided.

headline.main: The U.S. Has Fewer Crimes. Does That Mean It Needs Fewer Police?
headline.print_headline: Crime Is Falling, But Police Levels Remain Robust

docs.abstract: Disadvantaged people benefited the most from it. And nonprofits deserve more credit for it.
docs.snippet: Disadvantaged people benefited the most from it. And nonprofits deserve more credit for it.
docs.lead_paragraph: Over the past few years, the discussion of crime and violence in the United States has focused on police brutality, mass incarceration and the sharp rise in violence in cities like Baltimore, St. Louis and Chicago. This is entirely appropriate: Any spike in violence should garner attention, and redressing the injustices of our criminal justice system is a matter of moral urgency.

headline.main: Two Lessons of the Urban Crime Decline
